  "response_text": "The metric representing the average amount of actual available green biomass across all patches, accounting for reductions due to grazing, exhibits distinct trends over the time steps of the simulation. Initially, the mean green biomass starts at approximately 45,000 units. During the first 20 steps, there is a slight decline in the mean green biomass, reaching a low point around 44,000 units. Following this initial decline, the mean green biomass begins to increase steadily. This upward trend continues and accelerates significantly after the 40th step. By the 60th step, the mean green biomass has risen sharply, surpassing 55,000 units. The growth trend continues, albeit at a slower rate, and by the 100th step, the mean green biomass stabilizes around 62,000 units. This pattern indicates an initial period of biomass reduction followed by a substantial and sustained recovery phase, suggesting a dynamic interaction between grazing activities and biomass regeneration over time."
}

